# **4\. Mechanical Ground Support Equipment**

## **4.1 Scope of Project**

### 4.1.1 Problem

The development process of a CubeSat involves the following major stages:

* Assembly and Integration;  
* Qualification and Testing (TVAC and Vibration Testing);  
* Delivery to the Launch Integrator (Exolaunch).

Specialised Mechanical Ground Support Equipment (MGSE) are required to support each stage of the process. For Galassia-5, the MGSE must be custom-designed to support the in-house customised frame, external deployable solar panels and antennae, while also taking into account testing and transportation requirements (e.g. Interfaces to testing equipment)

### 4.1.2 Objective/Design Statement

* Develop in-house, dedicated Mechanical Ground Support Equipment (MGSE) custom-designed for Galassia-5 that **fully supports all phases** of the CubeSat development process, including assembly, integration, environmental qualification, and transportation to the launch site.   
* The MGSE shall be **specifically tailored** to the custom frame, deployables, and testing/transportation requirements of Galassia-5, and **enable safe handling of Galassia-5 from cleanroom through to launch vehicle integration**.

### 4.1.3 Current Progress

Currently, I am working on the Combined Assembly and TVAC Test Jig, with work on the Vibration Test Jig(s) and CubeSat Transport Case planned to begin in Semester 2\.

## **4.2 Design Requirements (Combined Assembly and TVAC Test Jig)**

The **Combined Assembly and TVAC Test Jig** should fulfil the following requirements:

* **Dimensions/Orientation:** Accommodate Galassia-5 (6U) in all 3 orientations. 

*  **Load Capacity:**  Carry Galassia-5’s full weight (approximately 9kg) plus safety margin.

*  **ESD Safe:**.Parts that contact the CubeSat must be ESD-safe to prevent the buildup and sudden discharge of static electricity, which can damage sensitive onboard electronics. Using ESD-safe materials ensures that any charge is instead safely dissipated..  
* **Low Outgassing:** Materials must meet ECSS low-outgassing requirements as the jig will be subject to vacuum conditions in the TVAC chamber. Outgassing occurs when materials release trapped/volatile gases while in vacuum, which can then condense onto critical surfaces such as optics and sensors, possibly degrading instrument performance.   
* **Portable within Cleanroom:** The Jig should be lightweight for portability.  
* **Clear Access to underside**: Adequate clearance to the bottom of the satellite is provided for integration and component testing.  
* **Ease of manufacture:** Manufacture and assembly of the Jig should be simple. The overall cost of the Jig should be far below options available on the market.

## **4.3 Concept Generation**

### 4.3.1 Concept Design for Jig

Current approaches by CubeSat manufacturers primarily utilise rotating jigs and base plates with removable stands. Although there are several commercial MGSE options available, these solutions typically cost several thousand dollars each.

**Rotating Jig**  
![Fine-tuned fixturing][image2] ![Image of 6U CubeSat integration rotating jig photo][image3]https://www.canadianmetalworking.com/canadianfabricatingandwelding/article/welding/fine-tuned-fixturing  
[https://www.endurosat.com/products/rotary-jig/](https://www.endurosat.com/products/rotary-jig/)

Rotating jigs consist of a circular base plate mounted on a turntable (either horizontal or vertical), with fixtures mounted to hold the CubeSat. The main advantage of such designs allow technicians to rotate the CubeSat easily to access all faces during assembly and integration. However, such designs are technically more complex to manufacture/assemble, require bearings, tend to be heavier, and require locking mechanisms to hold the CubeSat in place when working on the CubeSat.

**Base plate with Removable Stands**  
![A black rectangular object with metal partsAI-generated content may be incorrect.][image4]  
[https://www.cubesatshop.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/ISIS-Integration-Support-Jigs-Brochure-v1.pdf](https://www.cubesatshop.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/ISIS-Integration-Support-Jigs-Brochure-v1.pdf)

These Jigs consist of an Aluminium Base Plate with removable plastic/rubber stands, potentially allowing different CubeSat configurations (vertical/horizontal). As this design does not contain bearings or a turntable, it is easier to manufacture/assemble and more lightweight (making it more portable within the cleanroom).  
Although there is no rotating turntable, as the CubeSat and jig assembly is rather lightweight, technicians can shift the entire assembly as needed to access different parts during integration and testing.

**Decision Matrix**

|  | Rotating Jig | Base Plate with Stands/Support Brackets |
| :---: | :---: | :---: |
| Ease of access to different parts of CubeSat | \+ | 0 |
| Modularity (Ease of Configuration Change) | \- | \+ |
| Ease of transport | \- | \+ |
| Ease of manufacture/assembly | \- | \+ |
| Decision |  | ✔ |

### 4.3.2 Material Selection

Aluminium 6061, which is commonly available within NUS, is considered a suitable material for the base plate due to its sufficient mechanical strength and **low outgassing properties**. 

However, parts in contact with the CubeSat (such as the stands/fixtures) need to **additionally** **be ESD safe** and ideally made of plastic to prevent damage to the CubeSat’s frame. The Jig must be capable of operating within a temperature range of –15°C to \+55°C. This is derived from the operating temperature of the Simera Monoscope, which has the strictest operational limits of –10°C to \+50°C. In accordance with ECSS‐E‐ST‐10‐03C, a qualification margin of 5°C is applied at both the lower and upper ends of the temperature range.

According to ECSS‐Q‐ST‐70‐02C, the following must be met to ensure low outgassing:

* RML (Recovered Mass Loss) \<1.0%    
* CVCM (Collected Volatile Condensable Material) \<0.10 %

A TML (Total Mass Loss) of below 1.0% is preferred, though this can be ignored under certain circumstances. 

Some plastics were evaluated and presented in the decision matrix below:

| Material | ESD POM, e.g. Semitron ESd 225 (Acetal) | ESD ABS, e.g. ABS ESD-7 | CA3030 ESD PEKK |
| :---- | :---- | :---- | :---- |
| Resistance to Outgassing | **TML=1.40%;** RML=0.28%; CVCM=0.07% | TML=0.75%; RML=0.50%; CVCM=0.01% | TML=0.41%; RML=0.41%; CVCM=0.00% |
| ESD Safe | Yes | Yes | Yes |
| Glass Transition Temperature | 165°C | 105°C | 165°C |
| Price (per kg) | $270 | $140 | $980 |
| Decision |  | ✔ |  |

ESD POM was ruled out as its TML is above 1%. While PEKK has better performance overall, the cost is 8-9 times that of ESD ABS, which also fulfils all the requirements. Hence, ESD ABS was chosen.

Two main manufacturing options are considered for the manufacturing of the plastic components: CNC machining and 3D printing. While both methods are viable, the in-house 3D printing of ESD‐safe plastics is not practical. ESD plastics typically contain carbon black or carbon nanotubes, which can release volatile organic compounds (VOCs) and fine particulates during the printing process. Printing these materials requires an isolated printing environment equipped with thorough filtration and ventilation systems to ensure occupational safety and compliance with OSHA regulations. Thus, if 3D printing is chosen, this will need to be outsourced to qualified external vendors with proper control measures.

## **4.4 Detailed Design**

Several designs were developed to optimise the jig for supporting the CubeSat.

### 4.4.1 First Iteration 

The design consists of an Aluminum 6061 base plate of dimensions 400 x 260 x 100 mm. This allows enough space for the stands to be mounted, such that all 3 orientations (X, Y, or Z face facing down) of the CubeSat can be supported.  
![][image5]  
Fig. Base Plate V1. The Red, Magenta and Green lines denotes the CubeSat position for each orientation.

Two types of stands are mounted to the base plate from underneath using countersunk M5 screws, to accommodate different orientations of the CubeSat: 

* Corner towers (Vertical Orientation) – vertical ESD ABS posts that interfaces with the CubeSat rails at all 4 corners of the CubeSat, holding the CubeSat in the vertical position   
* Rail Blocks (Horizontal Orientation) – low-profile ESD ABS blocks that interfaces with the CubeSat rails. The Rail Blocks are spaced sufficiently far apart for the CubeSat rails at either edge of the CubeSat to fit snugly into the gap, holding the CubeSat in place.

The stands are raised to allow a 50 mm clearance beneath the CubeSat to provide access to bottom components.  
![][image6]![][image7]

Fig. Corner Tower \+ Rail Block

To validate the concept, a 3D-printed prototype was fabricated. Because the available printer (a Bambu Labs A1 Mini) did not have a sufficiently large build plate to accommodate the entire base plate in one piece, the base plate had to be downsized, split into four separate parts and put together using M3 screws. The hole positions for mounting the stands were not shifted.

A fit test was conducted using a 3D-printed mock-up of Galassia-5, and it was verified that the CubeSat fit properly in both the horizontal and vertical orientations onto the support brackets on the jig.

![][image8]  
Fig. Assembled Iteration 1 Jig with Galassia-5 3D-printed mockup (here shown in Vertical Orientation)

From the first prototype, some problems were observed:

* Based on CAD data, the total mass of the jig (if produced using the actual materials) would be close to 4kg (approx. 13kg with G5) , which was deemed too heavy to be portable.   
* During installation, there was difficulty aligning the screw holes on the stand with those on the base plate.  
* There is a possibility of the CubeSat Sliding/Toppling when being transported in the Horizontal Orientation.

### 4.4.2 Second Iteration 

To **reduce the weight of the Jig assembly**, material was removed from the base plate by cutting out holes. This brought the final mass of the aluminium base plate down to 1.8 kg, a reduction of around 40% compared to the original design.

| Overall Mass of Jig (empty) | First Iteration | Second Iteration |
| :---- | :---- | :---- |
| Horizontal Configuration | 4.0 kg | 2.6 kg |
| Vertical Configuration | 3.6 kg | 2.2 kg |

To **facilitate precise alignment during assembly**, 2 mm deep recesses matching the dimensions of the stands were machined into the base plate. This ensured that the screw holes would align accurately when the stands were placed into position. In accordance with Design for Manufacturing principles, T-bone fillets were incorporated into the recesses to provide suitable toolpaths for the milling cutter to ensure machinability. 

![][image9]  
Fig. Base Plate V2

To ensure that the holes cut would not affect the structural integrity of the Base Plate when subject to loads from Galassia-5, Finite Element Analysis (FEA) was conducted. A total load of 180N (twice the intended load) was applied, and a maximum stress of 5.27 \*10^6 N/m^2 was recorded. This is far below the yield stress of Al6061 (2.76\*10^8 N/m^2).

![][image10]  
Fig. FEA (both ends fixed, total load of 180N (twice the intended load))

To **prevent the CubeSat from toppling/sliding** off the rail blocks during transport, endblocks were designed to be installed onto the ends of the rail blocks using M3 screws.   
![][image11]![][image12]  
Fig. Endblock and hole interfaces on rail block

![][image13]  
Fig. CAD Render of Galassia-5 in Horizontal Orientation on the Jig with Endblocks installed

The proposed jig design demonstrates several unique features: 

* Its modular design enables support for all 3 orientations of Galassia-5, providing flexibility during testing and integration processes.   
* The jig is also Lightweight compared to other similar Jigs on the market, weighing only 2.6 kg compared to Endurosat’s 3.5 kg.  
* The design supports testing of deployable components by providing sufficient clearance around critical areas.   
* The Jig utilises materials with low outgassing properties, making it suitable for use in TVAC environments.   
* The endblock allows Galassia-5 to be securely fastened during transport, preventing toppling or sliding.

## **4.5 Future Work**

### 4.5.1 Possible Improvements to the Jig 

Based on the second prototype, the following areas for improvement are identified:

* **Handles** are to be procured and installed onto the jig for ease of transport within Cleanroom. Noting that handles may obstruct access to the CubeSat from certain angles, the handles should be easily removable with minimal and easily accessible screws.  
* **End block design** may need to be modified to ensure that the Solar Panel hinges are not obstructed (Pending confirmation of the solar panel hinge design)  
* **Modify Rail Block** to hold only the corners of the CubeSat. The current rail block design covers the entire longitudinal edge of the CubeSat, which prevents access to the underside/antenna deployment from the longitudinal edge.   
* **Modify screw holes to be accessible from above** for easier change of configuration. The stands are currently installed using screws fitted from below the assembly, which is inconvenient.   
* **Additional holes** will need to be made to bolt down Jig Assembly to the TVAC Chamber (Pending confirmation of TVAC Chamber to be used)

### 4.5.2 Future Work on other MGSE 

In Semester 2, design and prototyping work will be carried out on the following MGSE:

* Vibration Jig(s): Vibration Jigs to test the vibration performance of the CubeSat frame, in-house produced components such as the Ku Band Radio, will need to be designed. The effects of the Vibration Jigs on the Vibration test results (dynamic response) will need to be investigated.  
* A CubeSat Transport Case suitable to transport Galassia-5 to the launch integrator
